                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" id="assonance_sng_1" hclass="sense" fkcefr="c2"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">the effect created when two syllables in words that are close together have the same vowel sound, but different consonants, or the same consonants but different vowels, for example, <span class="ei">sonnet</span> and <span class="ei">porridge</span> or <span class="ei">cold</span> and <span class="ei">killed</span></span></span> <span class="xrefs" htag="span" xt="see" hclass="xrefs"><span class="prefix">see also</span> <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/alliteration" title="alliteration definition"><span class="xr-g" dict="all" bord="n" href="alliteration_e"><span class="xh">alliteration</span></span></a></span><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/language?level=c2" title="Topic language"><span class="topic" href="l2:communication:language?cefr=c2"><span class="topic_name">Language</span><span class="topic_cefr">c2</span></span></a></span><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="assonance_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">early 18th cent.: from French, from Latin <span class="ei">assonare</span> ‘respond to’, from <span class="ei">ad-</span> ‘to’ + <span class="ei">sonare</span> (from <span class="ei">sonus</span> ‘sound’).</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
